  <text>
    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Glenthorne Thursday</p>
      <p>Dearest W. I have decided to remain until tomorrow; in which I think I am not doing wrong or foolishly in any respect; even as regards my pursuits &amp; regular habits.</p>
      <p>You will be much interested when I relate to you (viva voce) all the history of our yesterday's expedition, which was in part almost hazardous, &amp; really quite singular altogether,</p>
      <p>both from the localities we passed &amp; from the state of the weather. I have too learned 2 new &amp; delightful expeditions for us to take from Ashley, being set down by our carriage in points I have noted of the Lymouth Road &amp; then wallking. And I look forward with delight to being your guide &amp; cicerone for once in this country!--</p>
      <p>I am extremely distressed &amp; concerned at a letter from Hester today; from which I really fear</p>
      <p>the C's are mad. I think I had better send it to you; for I am sure it will not make you condemn the C's unjustly &amp; hastily; &amp; that on the contrary, as I do myself, you will suspend your final judgment about them in this matter; making all allowance for justifiable disappointment just at first.</p>
      <p>But, if the Calliphronas's are permanently alienated from H--, I then rejoice in the present violent &amp; unbecoming nature of their conduct to Sir G; because it</p>
      <p>will probably prevent there being the slightest risk of his being influenced by them against H-- in her absence, (a thing I have dreaded); &amp; which a less open, but more prudent &amp; insidious line of conduct in them, might have made any possible I think. But how utterly inconsistent is this conduct with the tone of Charlotte's letter to me yesterday!--</p>
      <p>Let me hear from you by the groom, who goes over on Peter for some things of mine, &amp; takes this. I am anxious for</p>
      <p>your opinion on H's letter.</p>
      <p>I suppose we must write to Sir George himself now in a few days.</p>
      <p>So Halliday says he hears that Locke loses much by Beckham; &amp; gave for it a most preposterous &amp; fancy price; &amp; has no chance of selling it, with a strong anxiety to do so.</p>
      <p>The Knights are in Town; old K-- actually gone from Simm's Bath! But Halliday says they will now never budge him from the Burlington.</p>
      <p>Captain M-- came yesterday via Simm's Bath; which is how I heard.</p>
    </div></body>
